{
  "doc_id": "48503",
  "text": "Serum amyloid A (SAA) belongs to the family of apolipoproteins associated with high density lipoprotein [CITATION_1] . Different isoforms of SAA are expressed constitutively at different levels in response to inflammatory stimuli [CITATION_2] . During inflammation, SAA1 and SAA2 are expressed principally in the liver, whereas SAA3 is induced in many distinct tissues, including the mammary gland [CITATION_3] . The fourth isoform, SAA4, does not respond to external stimuli [CITATION_4] . The main functions of SAA are the reverse transport of cholesterol from tissue to hepatocytes, opsonisation, inhibition of phagocyte oxidative bursts and platelet activation [CITATION_5] ). The M-SAA3 isoform found in colostrum stimulates the production of mucin from intestinal cells and thus helps to prevent bacterial colonisation [CITATION_6] .",
